GitHub Repository:
Git Bash combines standard navigation commands with core Git version control commands to help Windows manage source code smoothly. [1]
📂 Navigation & File Management
These basic Bash commands help you move around folders and manage files before applying Git operations.
• : Prints the current absolute path of your active folder.
• : Lists files and directories in your current folder.
• : Lists all contents, including hidden files like .
• : Changes your directory to the specified folder path.
• : Moves up one directory level.
• : Creates a brand new folder.
• : Creates an empty file (e.g., ).
• : Permanently deletes a specified file.
• : Clears the entire terminal window for a clean screen. [4, 5, 6, 7, 8]

⚙️ Initial Setup
Use these configuration commands right after installing Git for Windows to establish your user identity.

• : Sets your commit author name globally.
• : Sets your commit author email globally.
• : Initializes a brand new local repository in your current folder.
• : Downloads an entire remote repository to your local computer. [1, 4, 10, 11, 12]

🛠️ Working with Changes (Staging & Committing)
These day-to-day commands track, stage, and save snapshots of your files.

• : Shows which files are modified, untracked, or ready to be staged.
• : Moves a specific file to the staging area.
• : Stages all new, modified, and deleted files at once.
• : Permanently saves your staged snapshot with a descriptive message.
• : Displays your chronological commit history in a clean, compact format.
• : Shows exact line-by-line differences of unstaged local changes. [4, 5, 14]

🌿 Branching & Merging
Isolate features or experiments securely without affecting your primary codebase.

• : Lists all local branches in the repository.
• : Generates a new branch without switching to it.
• : Switches your active environment to a different branch.
• : Creates a completely new branch and immediately switches to it.
• : Combines the specified branch's history into your current branch. [4, 11, 13, 14, 18, 19]

🌐 Synchronization (Remote Repositories)
Coordinate project changes across platforms like GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket.

• : Connects your local repository to a remote server link.
• : Verifies the specific URLs connected to your local repository.
• : Pulls down records of remote changes without overwriting local work.
• : Downloads updates and immediately merges them into your active branch.
• : Uploads your local commits to the remote database and links the branch paths. [1, 14, 18]

If you are trying to complete a specific task, let me know:

• Are you setting up a repository for the first time, or working with an existing project?
• Do you need to connect your local files to GitHub or another hosting platform?
• Are you encountering any errors like merge conflicts or access issues?



