TestNG: We can run testNG with help of creatin testNG.xml file with the helpof some command lines= mvn clean test -DsuiteXmlFile = testng.xml.
	In other way we can run it from the testNG.xml file by clicking Run AS > testng suite{TestNg plugin must be added for this to run the file.}

Record a Login test using Codegen:
Step-1: mvn exec:java -Dexec.args="codegen
		https://practicetestautomation.com/practice-test-login/"
		URL: could be changed according to the requriment.
Step-2: Record the login scenario & copy the java code in a new class loginTest.java.
Step-3: Extend from BaseTest, Update @Test annotation from testNG.
Step-4: Save & Run.
Step-5: Can also upadte the testNG.xml file & run from command line.
		URL: mvn clean test -DsuiteXmlFile=testNG.xml

Page Object Model{POM}: It's a design patter used in the test automation.
						* Where Object Locator and Object Action Methods communicate with Test Scrpits that call Object Methods.
						* Code becomes clean & clear, Objects and Object Action Methods are stored separately and Test Scripts are stored separately.
						* When any changes happend on the Action Methods just go to-> Page classof the particular page and make the changes accordingly.
						* It helps to write clean, reuseable and maintainable test code.
							Example: Each webpage=One class(LoginPage, HomePage)

That class contains:
Locator: How to find elements on the page [like buttons, inputs]
Action: What you can do [click, type, select ect]
How it helps-> Reusability, Readability, Maintainablity, Clean Code

Page Object Model:
Step-1: Understand the use case that we have to automate
		* Go to Login Page
		* Enter UserName, Password
		* Click Login/ Press Enter
		* Verify dashboard page is dispalyed [Dashboard Heading]
Step-2: Create Page classes under pages package according to the no. of pages we have to
		interact Example: For a LoginPage create 2 classes [LoginPage.java & HomePage.java]
Step-3: Under test package create a class LoginTest.java.
Step-4: Create/Record test scripts fpr the LoginTest.java.
Step-5: In LoginPage create add object locators & methods for actions on loginPage.java.
Step-6: Do the same in HomePage.java.
Step-7: Now in LogiTest.java create objects for Login Page & Home Page.
Step-8: Replace Scripts to call function's from page classes save & run.
Step-9: Add to testNG.XML run Using testNG.xml.

Extent Reports:
Step-1: Add extent reports dependency in Pom.xml.
Step-2: Create ExtentManage.java in src/test/java/util.
Step-3: Update the BaseTest.java.
Step-4: Use Login in your test [Optional].
Step-5: Run your test as testNG.xml or from cmd mvn clean test.
Step-6: Check Reports at test-output/ExtentReport.html.
Step-7: Can try skipping a test by adding the throw new skipException("Skipping for now").

Extent Reports by Screenshots on Failure:
Step-1: Create Screenshots in Utils package.
Step-2: Update in BaseTest to take Screenshots on failure in @AfterMethod.
Step-3: Create folder (if needed) test-output/Screenshots
Step-4: Save & Run the program.

Command Line step-by-step process
Step-1: Change the directory of the default one to the project directory
Step-2: Use mvn clean test
        *Cleans previous build results.
        *Compile & run all @Test classes in the floder src/test/java packages, for running the full suite.
Step-3: Use mvn -Dtest=LoginTest test
         *Run a specific test class
         *Login Test = class name
         *Runs only LoginTest.java file.
Step-4: Use mvn -Dtest=LOginTest#MethodName test
        *Run specific method in a test class.
        *Formate: ClassName#MethodName.
Step-5: Use mvn clean test -DsuiteXmlFile=testNG.XML file
        *Run tests using testNG.xml file.
        *Good for running test groups,  parallel tests, ect,.

Locators: Queries you use to find & interact with elements[buttons, inputs, links, ect] on a web page
Step-1: Create a new java class in the floder src/test/java packages LocatorTest.java.
Step-2: Add a function testAllLocators() & add testNG annotation @Test.
Step-3: Navigate to the URL of the web page.
Step-4: Now create locators from the objects as needed for the test.

Do's: Use Id, name, value, getByText() for buttons, getByRole() for accessibility.
Don'ts: Avoid auto-generated classes, absolute Xpaths, don't hardcode index unless it is stable.